<article id="post-20904" class="post-20904 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-covid-19 tag-chris-sciabarra tag-coronavirus tag-covid-19 tag-covid-19-narratives tag-medicine">
	<header class="entry-header">

		<h1 class="entry-title"><a href="https://irfankhawajaphilosopher.com/2020/03/29/covid-19-narrative-2-chris-matthew-sciabarra/" rel="bookmark">COVID-19 Narrative (2): Chris Matthew&nbsp;Sciabarra</a></h1>
				<div class="entry-meta">
			Posted on <a href="https://irfankhawajaphilosopher.com/2020/03/29/covid-19-narrative-2-chris-matthew-sciabarra/" title="3:43 pm" rel="bookmark"><time class="entry-date" datetime="2020-03-29T15:43:52-04:00" pubdate>March 29, 2020</time></a><span class="byline"> by <span class="author vcard"><a class="url fn n" href="https://irfankhawajaphilosopher.com/author/khawajaenator/" title="View all posts by Irfan Khawaja" rel="author">Irfan Khawaja</a></span></span><span class="cats-links"> under <a href="https://irfankhawajaphilosopher.com/tag/covid-19/" rel="category tag">COVID-19</a></span>					</div><!-- .entry-meta -->
		
	</header><!-- .entry-header -->

		<div class="entry-content">
		<p><em>This is the second in my series of <a href="https://irfankhawajaphilosopher.com/covid19narrativeproject/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">COVID-19 Narratives,</a> by my dear friend <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chris_Matthew_Sciabarra" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Chris Sciabarra</a>, sheltering in place in Brooklyn, New York. Though the series is primarily about what I called the &#8220;supply side&#8221; of the health care equation during this crisis, I wanted to run some posts that described the &#8220;demand side&#8221; as well, that is, what it&#8217;s like to be a patient during the pandemic. Particularly valuable about Chris&#8217;s post is how it illustrates the implications of the COVID-19 pandemic for people with serious medical conditions whose previously scheduled medical procedures have now been deemed &#8220;elective.&#8221; &#8220;Elective&#8221; in this context doesn&#8217;t mean &#8220;optional.&#8221; It means downgraded to second or third priority out of sheer, dire necessity: hospital beds, equipment, and personnel have to be left vacant or unused to absorb the overwhelming crush of COVID-19 patients we expect to see. And even at the center of the pandemic, we haven&#8217;t yet reached the peak of that crush.</em> <a href="https://irfankhawajaphilosopher.com/2020/03/29/covid-19-narrative-2-chris-matthew-sciabarra/#more-20904" class="more-link">Continue reading <span class="meta-nav">&rarr;</span></a></p>
			</div><!-- .entry-content -->
	
	<footer class="entry-meta">

				<span class="comments-link"><a href="https://irfankhawajaphilosopher.com/2020/03/29/covid-19-narrative-2-chris-matthew-sciabarra/#comments">9 Comments</a></span>
		
	</footer><!-- .entry-meta -->
</article><!-- #post-20904 -->

				
					
